<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF96639CFC4CFC8817AB" bold="true" box="[151,819,903,930]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<taxonomicName id="E7C14D0DC828FF96639CFC4CFD7317AB" authority="Salles, Marulanda &amp; Dias" authorityName="Salles &amp; Marulanda &amp; Dias" authorityYear="2018" box="[151,712,903,930]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Atopophlebia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF96639CFC4CFEC717A8" bold="true" box="[151,380,903,929]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Atopophlebia pacis</emphasis>
Salles, Marulanda &amp; Dias
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="098657E7C828FF9661DDFC43FC8817AB" box="[726,819,904,930]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF96639CFC61FE7417CA" blockId="1.[151,819,903,963]" box="[151,463,938,963]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
(
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966395FC61FEB217CA" box="[158,265,938,963]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Figures 1</figureCitation>
to 12, 26 and 27)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68DB6505C828FF96639CFC39FE8510EA" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF96639CFC39FE8510EA" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF96639CFC39FEAA1002" bold="true" box="[151,273,1010,1035]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male imago of 
<taxonomicName id="E7C14D0DC828FF96610AFC39FD661002" authority="Salles &amp; Marulanda &amp; Dias, 2018" authorityName="Salles &amp; Marulanda &amp; Dias" authorityYear="2018" box="[513,733,1010,1035]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Atopophlebia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF96610AFC39FD661002" box="[513,733,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Atopophlebia pacis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="098657E7C828FF9661E6FC39FCF11002" box="[749,842,1010,1035]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" rank="species">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9661E6FC39FCF11002" bold="true" box="[749,842,1010,1035]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, can be distinguished from the other species of the genus by the following combination of characteristics: 1) Eyes meeting on meson of head; 2) Fore wings hyaline, veins yellow (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966231FBF1FE3A105A" box="[314,385,1082,1107]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); 3) Fore tibia completely tinged with black; 4) Abdominal segments yellowish, terga VIII with conspicuous triangular anterolateral black mark (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF9661FEFB95FC8D107E" box="[757,822,1118,1143]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); 5) Apical projection of penis lobe short (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF96661CFB95FAE7107E" box="[1303,1372,1118,1143]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). The nymph can be distinguished from the other species of the genus by the following combination of characteristics: 1) Labial palp segment I strongly widened, 0.7 times as wide as long (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966081FB6DFC6610B6" box="[906,989,1190,1215]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); 2) Abdominal color pattern as in male imago (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF9663E7FB01FE8B10EA" box="[236,304,1226,1251]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68DB6505C828FF9563CCFB25FB3A15FC" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="140" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" type="description">
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF9663CCFB25FA32110F" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" box="[199,1417,1262,1287]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9663CCFB25FDBB110E" bold="true" box="[199,512,1262,1287]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Description of male imago</emphasis>
(in alcohol). 
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF96619CFB25FD4B110E" box="[663,752,1262,1287]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Lengths</emphasis>
: body: 
<quantity id="E7399B6BC828FF96604EFB25FC17110F" box="[837,940,1262,1287]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.25" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="7.25">7.25 mm</quantity>
; fore wings: 
<quantity id="E7399B6BC828FF966735FB25FB2D110F" box="[1086,1174,1262,1287]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="139" unit="mm" value="7.6">7.6 mm</quantity>
; hind wings: 1.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF9663CCFAD9FD981122" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" box="[199,547,1298,1323]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9663CCFAD9FE1C1122" box="[199,423,1298,1323]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">General coloration:</emphasis>
yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF9663CCFAFDFCA2117A" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9663CCFAFDFEBF1146" box="[199,260,1334,1359]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes meeting on meson of head. Head yellowish orange. Lateral ocellus surrounded with black. Upper portion of turbinate eyes orange, lower portion dark grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF9663CCFAB5FD2C1242" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9663CCFAB5FE9A119E" box="[199,289,1406,1431]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Thorax:</emphasis>
General color yellowish with three black lines in the pronotum mid-part; pleural sclerites washed with dark grey. Forewing (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966287FA69FE6811B2" box="[396,467,1442,1467]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
): maximum width 0.4 times maximum length; membrane hyaline, veins yellow; vein MP2 attached at base to MP1; IMP attached at base to veins MP1 and MP2. Hind wing (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF96679EFA0DFB6111D6" box="[1173,1242,1478,1503]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) base pigmented with gray; costal projection located on apical 0.65, apex of wing roundly acute; 3 cross veins present. Fore femur orange; fore tibia completely tinged with black. Middle and hind legs orange; middle and hind tibiae washed with brown. Patella-tibial suture absent on all legs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF9663CCF99DFC6012F7" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9663CCF99DFE8A1266" box="[199,305,1622,1647]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Abdomen</emphasis>
: yellowish with intersegmental membrane between segments I to VIII tinged with diffuse black; terga I with lateral margin tinged with diffuse black, terga VIII with black anterolateral triangular mark and anteromedial black spot (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF9662BBF955FE4A12BE" box="[432,497,1694,1719]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal sterna pale yellowish; subgenital plate and forceps yellow (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF96662AF955FF1312D2" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Figs. 3 and 4</figureCitation>
). Penes fused in basal 1/3 with lobes 0.3 times as wide as long; each lobe with an apical short projection directed ventro-laterally (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966258F92DFE5C12F6" box="[339,487,1766,1791]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Figs. 3 and 4</figureCitation>
). Cerci and terminal filaments brownish tan.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC828FF9663CCF8C1FD3313DE" blockId="1.[151,1437,1010,2007]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF9663CCF8C1FDD8132A" bold="true" box="[199,611,1802,1827]" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Description of nymph (immature).</emphasis>
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC828FF966160F8C1FD0B132A" box="[619,688,1802,1827]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Head:</emphasis>
yellowish brown, vertex diffusely tinged with black; area anterior to median ocellus yellow, triangular (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966148F8E5FD32134E" box="[579,649,1838,1863]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Labrum (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966000F8E5FCEA134E" box="[779,849,1838,1863]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) with lateral margins slightly angled, distal margin with broad and flat denticles, except for the median denticle, which is narrower and rounded apically (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF96664DF899FA351362" box="[1350,1422,1874,1899]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Mandible (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF96621AF8BDFEE81386" box="[273,339,1910,1935]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) diffusely tinged with black on exposed dorsal surface. Maxilla (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966722F8BDFBD71386" box="[1065,1132,1910,1935]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) with outer margin of stipe tinged with black. Hypopharynx with apex of superlingua strongly curved. Labium (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC828FF966742F851FB2513BA" box="[1097,1182,1946,1971]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="139">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
): labial palp segment I strongly widened, 0.7 times as wide as long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC82BFF9563CCFF5CFA2D1581" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC82BFF9563CCFF5CFEA314B9" box="[199,280,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Thorax</emphasis>
: yellowish brown with black marks on anterior and lateral margins of mesonotum (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC82BFF9567C8FF5CFAB314B9" box="[1219,1288,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Legs (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC82BFF95666FFF5CFEB214DD" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Figs. 11 and 12</figureCitation>
) yellowish white; fore femur with subapical pale brown mark; mid femur missing; hind femur almost completely pigmented by pale brown. Foreleg (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC82BFF9561BAFF14FCBE14F1" box="[689,773,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
): femur with outer margin with row of long and fine setae along distal ¾ and row of spatulate setae, little shorter than fine setae, on distal ½; anterior surface with few short blunt setae on distal ½. Hind leg (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC82BFF956118FEECFDDC1549" box="[531,615,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 6–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[190,1394,254,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,230,1895]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 6–12. Atopophlebia pacis, sp. nov., mouthparts (6 to 10) and legs (11 and 12) of nymph: 6) labrum; 7) detail of distal margin of labrum; 8) left mandible; 9) maxilla; 10) labium; 11) fore leg; 12) hind leg." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437330/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
): femur with few fine setae on outer margin, spatulate setae present from base to apex; anterior surface with short blunt setae more numerous and more spread than in foreleg; tibia with few spatulate setae on outer margin. Tarsal claws with a row of 5–8 denticles, the apical denticle larger than the others.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC82BFF9563CCFE5FFB3A15FC" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC82BFF9563CCFE5FFE8115A4" box="[199,314,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Abdomen:</emphasis>
yellowish brown with black markings as in male imago, except that segment II is tinged as segment I and conspicuous marks on segments VIII are also present on segment VII (
<figureCitation id="B8FA2A0BC82BFF9560E0FE7CFB9415D9" box="[1003,1071,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[237,1343,230,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[198,1392,195,1951]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Atopophlebia pacis sp. nov., male imago (1 to 4) and nymph (5): 1) dorsal view of abdomen; 2) forewing and hind wing; 3) genitalia, dorsal view; 4) genitalia, lateral view; 5) habitus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1437328/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Gills grayish, tracheae black, a large basal lobe on inner lamella; seventh gill much reduced. Caudal filaments yellowish.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="68DB6505C82BFF9563CCFE34FD8016AE" pageId="2" pageNumber="140" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="207E368EC82BFF9563CCFE34FAA61669" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC82BFF9563CCFE34FEF51611" bold="true" box="[199,334,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet of the new species is derived from the latin word for peace and is a reference to the peace process between the Revolutionary Armed Forces of 
<collectingCountry id="58D6761EC82BFF956046FDEFFC001634" box="[845,955,548,573]" name="Colombia" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectionCode id="46D0AE4BC82BFF9560C6FDEFFBA31635" box="[973,1048,548,572]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">FARC</collectionCode>
) and the Colombian government. Thanks to that, this taxon could be finally collected, identified as a new species and properly described.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207E368EC82BFF9563CCFDA7FD8016AE" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">
<emphasis id="12B5EA9CC82BFF9563CCFDA7FE68168C" bold="true" box="[199,467,620,645]" pageId="2" pageNumber="140">Life cycle association.</emphasis>
Nymphs and adults were collected in the same area and both share the same and conspicuous abdominal color pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
